content: Today, I will continue showing games from Helsinki Open
Hope we can learn something form these Estonian masters
we went through some games from rounds 1-3
Today I will start with an interesting game from round 4
between Timo Ilu and Ants Soosyrv
Hope you will be awake during this session

Liuchao, skywalker, Whiz, alicecooper, chess, Adun, yuelee00, mayhem, Samsone, lkogr, danfengyue, blueice, shuwang, verne, Torsten, yaya, Andry, ice, slamduk, xuwu, xinxin, benben, slappanu, LiuJianping, mima, Renju_liu_t.
In the game, Timo was black and chose I12 opening, Ants kept whites
which one do you think was played ?
Ants preferred the variant of E8
Many of you might find this familiar, after many lessons given here by GM Kawamura
Your opinions about this move, please
How about the other stuents present ?
not very good for black maybe
not sure if white had counters at the top
Andry, care to share your idea why not good ? :)
what would be your respond here then
he made mistake in the end
better not ask anymore from him :)
Ants kind of bravely decided to cut the space attack
which seems like the smartest thing to do
going to middle would result in getting surrounded by blacks
had to block the line 3-19 anyway
Timo's respond was quite tough also
kind of signaling that passive defense might not be enough anymore
do you have an idea Torsten ?
one can cut it and win
how would you play blacks now
So, maybe Ants wants to see this ?
maybe just giving his opponent a chance :))
there was enough time I think
one has a lot of respect playing aganst Ants :)
when strong opponent makes tricky moves, it makes you wonder
if no win, in big trouble.
why do you think Ants chose here then
yes verne, it creates a VCF threat
and also is a helpful stone, if further on fight moves to upper area
here, is the moment Andry spoke of earlier
So, in this game a lot happened
which turned out to be a bad mistake
later on white missed own win
After the 4th round, and the 1st day, we had 2 player with full 4 points
here, the game expectedly turns to i11
usually white chooses 8th to i7 or i10
I'm not sure how familiar Johann was with this variant
possibly Johann chose here in order to have better chances to win, or do you know Andry ?
he didnt want t play the theory
because stefan knows the variants better
8-i7 tends to make the game pretty easy for black to force atleast draw
maybe Stefan was not so familiar with the variant
by 16th white secured a pretty good start
better than with other 8th moves, I think
black is down to one area basically
can you explain, why 18th so deep inside ?
cut off as much as possible
it leaves black very few choices
As a homework, you will somehow investigate other black choices here
21 plans to keep tempo while eliminating white material on left
black may play 21 - h4 then 23 - g3
yes, here it seems not so good
by now black attack has died for sure
The games lasted about 40 stones from here on
white did not win easily, Stefan defended quite well
but in the end, maybe from time trouble, he was forcedto a 3x3
and Johann got the win with this new tactics
not very important, it was maybe fight against time by then
but here there was quite much happenings also
we have a rare 8th move tactics
can not say, if this 11th is best
and it resulted in immediate black troubles
despite the seemingly poor position, black managed to defend well all around
he defended the lower side, the right side, and the upper right side
but was caught on top left

skywalker, Samsone, chess, mayhem, Ikon, Torsten, slappanu, tianxia, Liuchao, Andry, benben, ice, yuelee00, LiuJianping, blueice, Timo, verne, Whiz, Renju_liu_t, shuwang, lkogr, xuwu, Adun, xiaoxin, mima, yaya, slamduk, derkas, xinxin, alicecooper.
on 6th round, a very crucial game concerning tournament win was played
thsi variant likely familiar to you ?
I had maybe win with Andry there, and this maybe win turned out as loss :)
perhaps here are many elements speaking for draw
but also some variants, where other gets good attacks
which often leads to an equal game
Tunnet's play was new to me
then he moves to lower side
can Timo give us any thoughts you had of this move ?
indeed it seems to be a connection point
tunnet sayd after the game that 40-42 wins
would anyone want to try win here
I will sit back and let you play it
comes back to the real game
so perhaps we assume it is not VCF
it's a must, but also a good block
so if we can not chage 43rd
L5 is win, and n10 is foul
so, Tunnet knew there was win, but failed to find it in such short time limit
time was only 40mins for the game
if 43 down, then win to L8 as Torsten said
in the game Tunnet played differently
with 51st move, black moves closer to left side
even with otehr 52nd moves, black position seems very good
unfortunate for Tunnet, he misplayed his nice win chance by 40-42
we can not declare it is sure win having not discussed all possibly blocks
so maybe draw game was very interesting
27th like this surely gives this playing chance
it gives white chance to use to 3x3 threat to k14
maybe black could play 27th differently to avoid this help line to white
but that is a whole new discussion
Today, we saw some quite interesting games
and luckily we found some nice wins that the players missed
all in all, maybe a fine lesson
but perhaps, I would have been better off doing more groundwork before the lesson :(
Ok, in the future I will demonstrate to you the exciting last round of the tournament !
